data.title: New scheme has Packers defensive linemen in attack mode
data.meta_description: Job responsibilities will change from prior years for the defensive linemen, who welcome a new coordinator in Jeff Hafley.
data.text:
GREEN BAY — While Jason Rebrovich probably won’t bring back the analogy he used during the offseason comparing his guys to a Navy SEALS team, the Green Bay Packers defensive line coach was right in his assertion that new coordinator Jeff Hafley’s system does rely on the front four generating pressure and stuffing the run.

“We’re the first line of defense. The rest of the guys are going to sit back there and do what they need to do. We are going to work to get our forces in first,” Rebrovich explained in the spring. “If that force goes in and is able to create that great opportunity for us defensively, then let’s go.”

Hafley’s 4-3 system — which, in truth, will be primarily a 4-2-5 operation, playing more nickel packages than base defenses — will most often have two linebackers on the field instead of three, putting an even greater onus on the four linemen to take care of business.

It also means that, because of the amount of effort Hafley demands the big fellas up front exert, you’ll see more frequent substitutions to keep guys fresh.

“With this system, you’ve got to play like that. You can’t be out there like six snaps in a row and exert that much energy and make an impact on this defense,” veteran Pro Bowl defensive tackle Kenny Clark said. “With this defense, you’ve got to be able to go and really get off the ball and give that energy and that effort every single play. So, we’ll definitely be rotating a lot this season.”

With that in mind, here are the four biggest issues, questions or storylines on the defensive line heading into training camp, which kicks off with the team’s first full-squad practice next Monday.

Hafley’s scheme is predicated on a fierce defensive front. Do the Packers have that?

Hafley sure thinks so, and so does Rebrovich, who insists that his group will benefit from the more aggressive tack defensive linemen get to take.

“I’m sure you’ve heard it. It’s an ‘attack’ front,” Rebrovich said. “It’s about TFLs and sacks. We’re going to look to create havoc in the backfield. Every down, we’re looking to penetrate and make something big happen.”

In addition to Clark, T.J. Slaton and Karl Brooks inside, the Packers’ outside linebackers-turned-defensive ends — Preston Smith, Rashan Gary, Lukas Van Ness and Kingsley Enagbare most prominently — will be the tone-setters coming off the edge. But in passing situations, don’t be surprised if Van Ness lines up inside to generate a greater interior pass rush.

“His growth, he’s not even scratching the surface, man,” Gary said of Van Ness, the team’s first-round pick a year ago. “He’s just starting. I know it’s going to be a big jump (this) year because he has the same type of work ethic as me and he’s hungry for everything he has in front of him. He understands what he needs to work on and I know he’s going to get better at it. I just can’t wait to see him tear it up.”

Will this system finally yield an effective run defense?

Ex-Packers right tackle Bryan Bulaga, who saw a variation of this style of defense in practice during his two-year stint with the Los Angeles Chargers, likes to call the run defense approach, “Playing the run on the way to the quarterback.”

That’s because the linemen are no longer responsible for the gaps on either side of them; rather, they are simply responsible for one gap and can attack that gap without having to read the play first. That allows them to get upfield if the quarterback is dropping back to pass or to disrupt a running play before it gets going.

Of course, that also could lead to big holes if a player gets washed out of his gap or the offense uses his aggressiveness against him.

Then again, given how the Packers have struggled to stop the run in recent years, regardless of scheme or coordinator, it’s worth a try.

“For the D-line, they’re going to be asked to do some different things than they would playing in 3-4 spacing. Some are going to have their hand down on the ground more,” Hafley said. “But when it comes to getting off blocks and tackling, those guys have all done that. It’s just sharpening it, making it better.”

How will 2022 first-round pick Devonte Wyatt respond in what looks to be a make-or-break year?

Wyatt’s first two NFL seasons have been largely meh. He’s flashed at times, but certainly not as often as you’d like for a first-round pick. There seems to be universal agreement inside the building, though, that if any system will bring out the best in him, this is it.

Wyatt himself said he must take a “monster leap” this season, and he believes this system, which will have him attacking more and thinking less, will lead to such a leap.

“Me personally, I think (the scheme change) will be good. It will help me focus on one thing and not a lot of things,” said Wyatt, who had 36 tackles (18 solo), 5.5 sacks, six tackles for loss, 11 quarterback hits and recovered a fumble while playing 552 regular-season defensive snaps (49.7%) last season. “I just feel like it gave me the best chance to attack, attack, attack instead of reading and reacting.”

What does the future hold for Clark, the team’s longest-tenured player?

Clark is in the final year of his contract, and while he entered the league at such a young age as a 2016 first-round pick that he’s still somehow only 28 years old — he’ll turn 29 in October — there’s reason to wonder if he’s playing his final season in Green Bay.

Given the Packers’ undeniable trend toward moving on from older players, it’s noteworthy that he’s playing out the four-year, $70 million contract extension he signed in August 2020 — at a $27.5 million cap number this season and an additional $13.7 million cap charge in 2025, whether he’s on the team or not.

“There’s been talks, still ongoing,” Clark said during the Packers’ mandatory minicamp last month. “They’re talking, though, and that’s the only thing I got on that.

“I love it here. I love my teammates. I love the organization. Hopefully everything will work out.”
